### Fauna

The city boasts diverse wetland [habitats](/Habitat), including the Gaulosen, where an observation tower facilitates birdwatching and educational displays on avian life. [35]

Despite being Norway's third-largest city, Trondheim is no stranger to wildlife. [European otters](/European_otter) and [European beavers](/European_beaver) are known to inhabit the [Nidelva](/Nidelva) and [Bymarka](/Bymarka) areas. [Eurasian badgers](/Eurasian_badger) and [red foxes](/Red_fox) are not uncommon sightings. Majestic [moose](/Moose) and various [deer](/Deer) species are frequently seen in the surrounding hills, occasionally venturing into the city, particularly in May when young are driven from their mothers, or in late winter when food becomes scarce. A [wolverine](/Wolverine) even made its home in Bymarka from 2002 to 2017. [37] [38]

### Cityscape and sites

*Central Trondheim as seen from the tower of the Nidaros Cathedral looking towards [Trondheim Fjord](/Trondheim_Fjord) and [Munkholmen](/Munkholmen) Island*
*The city's central square (Torvet) in 2020*
*The pavement cafes at Bakklandet*
*Bakke Bridge*

[DORA 1](/DORA_1), a formidable [German submarine](/U-boat) base from the Second World War, once housed the [13th U-boat Flotilla](/13th_U-boat_Flotilla). Today, its concrete structure safeguards various archives, including the city and university archives. It has also found a new life as a concert venue.

Perched on a hill east of the city, [Kristiansten Fortress](/Kristiansten_Fortress), constructed between 1681 and 1684, successfully repelled a Swedish invasion in 1718. It was eventually decommissioned in 1816.

In the city's central square stands a statue of [Olav Tryggvason](/Olav_Tryggvason), the city's founder, atop an obelisk. The base of the statue serves as a [sun dial](/Sun_dial), though its accuracy is skewed by an hour during summer due to its calibration to UTC+1.

The islet of Munkholmen, a popular tourist and recreational spot, has a history as a site of execution, a [monastery](/Monastery), a [fortress](/Fortress), a [prison](/Prison), and a WWII [anti-aircraft](/Anti-aircraft) emplacement.

[Stiftsgården](/Stiftsg%C3%A5rden), the royal residence in Trondheim, originally built in 1774, is a colossal wooden structure—possibly the largest in [Northern Europe](/Northern_Europe)—boasting 140 rooms and spanning 4,000 square meters (43,056 sq ft). It has served royalty and their guests since 1800.

A replica statue of [Leif Ericson](/Leif_Ericson) graces the seaside, near the old Customs Building and cruise ship facilities. The original stands in a [marina](/Marina) in Seattle.

The [Nidelva](/Nidelva) river meanders through Trondheim, its banks lined with historic storehouses. The picturesque [Old Town Bridge](/Old_Town_Bridge) is a prominent feature in this riverside panorama.

#### Shopping

Trondheim's city center is a charming labyrinth of independent boutiques. The primary shopping arteries are the pedestrianized Nordre gate, Olav Tryggvasons gate, and Thomas Angells gate, offering a mix of established brands and trendy newcomers.

In the late 1990s, the derelict industrial area of [Nedre Elvehavn](/Nedre_Elvehavn), once home to [Trondhjems mekaniske Værksted](/Trondhjems_mekaniske_V%C3%A6rksted), was transformed into a residential and commercial hub. The shopping center Solsiden emerged, becoming a popular spot, especially among younger demographics.

For larger retail experiences, the eastern suburb of Lade-Strindheim, along Haakon VIIs gate and Bromstadvegen, and the southern suburb of Tiller, centered around [City Syd](/City_Syd), offer extensive shopping. Swedish retailers like [IKEA](/IKEA), [Biltema](/Biltema), and [Clas Ohlson](/Clas_Ohlson) have a strong presence in these areas, particularly in the DIY and apparel sectors.

### Nidaros Cathedral

The [Nidaros Cathedral](/Nidaros_Cathedral) and the adjacent Archbishop's Palace form a significant historical and spiritual nexus in the city center. The cathedral, begun around 1070, stands as Norway's preeminent [Gothic](/Gothic_architecture) monument and was once Northern Europe's most vital [pilgrimage](/Pilgrimage) destination during the Middle Ages, drawing pilgrims from as far as [Oslo](/Oslo) and parts of Sweden. Today, it holds the distinction of being the world's northernmost medieval cathedral and Scandinavia's second largest.

*West front of [Nidaros Cathedral](/Nidaros_Cathedral)*

Historically, the Nidaros Cathedral served as the [coronation](/Coronation) church for Norwegian monarchs, both during the Middle Ages and following the restoration of independence in 1814. King [Haakon VII](/Haakon_VII_of_Norway) was the last to be crowned there in 1906. Since 1957, with [King Olav V](/Olav_V_of_Norway), coronations were replaced by [consecration](/Consecration). The current King [Harald V](/Harald_V_of_Norway) and [Queen Sonja](/Queen_Sonja_of_Norway) underwent this ceremony in 1991. A notable event occurred on May 24, 2002, when their daughter, [Princess Märtha Louise](/Princess_M%C3%A4rtha_Louise_of_Norway), married [Ari Behn](/Ari_Behn) within its hallowed walls. [40] [41]

The ancient [Pilgrim's Route](/Pilgrim%27s_Route) (Pilegrimsleden) to St. Olav's tomb at [Nidaros](/Nidaros) Cathedral has been revived. Known also as St. Olav's Way (Sankt Olavs vei), the primary path, approximately 640 kilometers (400 mi) long, begins in [Oslo](/Oslo), traces the shores of Lake [Mjøsa](/Mj%C3%B8sa), winds through the [Gudbrandsdalen](/Gudbrandsdalen) valley, crosses the [Dovrefjell](/Dovrefjell) mountains, and descends through the [Oppdal](/Oppdal_Municipality) valley to its destination in Trondheim. A Pilgrim's Office in Oslo offers guidance, and a Pilgrim Centre in Trondheim, operating under the cathedral's auspices, issues certificates to those who complete the journey. [42] [43]

