### Museums

[Sverresborg](/Sverresborg), once a fortification built by [Sverre Sigurdsson](/%C3%98retinget) and named after [King David](/King_David)'s castle in [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem), now operates as an open-air museum featuring over 60 buildings. The original castle, constructed in 1182–1183, was short-lived, burning down in 1188, though the [Sverresaga](/Sverresaga) indicates its restoration by 1197. [44] [Citation needed]

The Trondheim Science Center ([Vitensenteret i Trondheim](/Vitensenteret_i_Trondheim)) offers interactive scientific exhibits. The [NTNU University Museum](/NTNU_University_Museum), part of the [Norwegian University of Science and Technology](/Norwegian_University_of_Science_and_Technology), showcases various collections. The city also hosts smaller museums dedicated to history, science, and [natural history](/Natural_history), including the Trondheim Maritime Museum, the Armoury adjacent to the Archbishop's Palace, Kristiansten Fortress, the [Ringve National Museum](/Ringve_National_Museum) focusing on music and instruments, Ringve Botanical Garden, the [Trondheim Tramway Museum](/Trondheim_Tramway_Museum), and the Jewish Museum, co-located with one of the world's northernmost synagogues.

[Rockheim](/Rockheim), the National Museum of Pop and Rock, opened in August 2010. Housed in a repurposed warehouse, its distinctive box-shaped roof, adorned with thousands of color-changing lights, has become a recognizable landmark, especially during the dark winter months.

### Prison

Vollan District Jail ([Vollan kretsfengsel](/Vollan_kretsfengsel)) served as a prison during the [Nazi occupation of Norway](/Nazi_occupation_of_Norway), holding both prisoners of war and criminals. It was not classified as a [concentration camp](/Concentration_camp). [45] Records indicate numerous POWs were held at Vollan, some serving as [transit camps](/Internment) for [political prisoners](/Political_prisoners). Many were subsequently taken to [Kristiansten Fortress](/Kristiansten_Fortress) and executed. Interrogations often took place at the Mission Hotel or were conducted by [Henry Rinnan](/Henry_Rinnan) and his associates. [45] Vollan closed in 1971, replaced by Trondheim Prison at Tunga.

Trondheim Prison ([Trondheim fengsel](/Trondheim_fengsel)) is part of the Northern Region of the [Norwegian Correctional Services](/Norwegian_Correctional_Services) and accommodates 184 [inmates](/Inmates). It comprises four main departments:

• Nermarka ("Tunga") – a closed facility.
• Detention department at Nermarka.
• Leira – an open division focused on rehabilitation through social activities. [47]
• Kongens gt. division – a halfway house located downtown.

### Attractions

The [Pirbadet](/Pirbadet), a popular [water park](/Water_park) and [public pool](/Public_pool), is situated on the Brattøra district's northern shore, a short walk from the central train station.

### Wider urban area

Trondheim serves as the core of the [Trondheim Region](/Trondheim_Region), a significant hub for employment, commerce, and healthcare. While official definitions of Norway's [metropolitan areas](/Metropolitan_area) are broad, the zone of reciprocal commuting—where Trondheim residents also seek services—encompasses Trondheim, [Malvik Municipality](/Malvik_Municipality), central [Stjørdal](/Stj%C3%B8rdal) (including [Værnes](/V%C3%A6rnes)), central [Melhus Municipality](/Melhus_Municipality), [Skaun Municipality](/Skaun_Municipality), and the lower reaches of [Vanvikan](/Vanvikan) in [Indre Fosen Municipality](/Indre_Fosen_Municipality). [48]

### Government

*Trondheim's town hall.*

Trondheim Municipality oversees essential public services, including [primary education](/Primary_education), outpatient [health services](/Health_care), elder care, [welfare](/Welfare_spending) and social services, [zoning](/Zoning), [economic development](/Economic_development), and municipal infrastructure. The municipality is governed by a [municipal council](/Municipal_council_(Norway)) elected for four-year terms, with the [mayor](/Mayor) chosen through an indirect election by the council members. [49] Legal matters fall under the jurisdiction of the [Trøndelag District Court](/Tr%C3%B8ndelag_District_Court) and the [Frostating Court of Appeal](/Frostating_Court_of_Appeal).

In 2005, the city was reorganized from five to four [boroughs](/Borough), each with its own social services office. The current boroughs are [Midtbyen](/Midtbyen,_Trondheim) (44,967 inhabitants), [Østbyen](/%C3%98stbyen) (42,707 inhabitants), [Lerkendal](/Lerkendal,_Trondheim) (46,603 inhabitants), and [Heimdal](/Heimdal) (30,744 inhabitants), with population figures as of January 1, 2008. Prior to 2005, Trondheim was divided into the boroughs Sentrum, Strinda, Nardo, Byåsen, and Heimdal.

• See also: [List of mayors of Trondheim](/List_of_mayors_of_Trondheim)

