### Education and research

*NTNU's main building*

See also the [list of primary schools in Trondheim](/Okstad_School).

Trondheim is a significant educational center, hosting the [Norwegian University of Science and Technology](/Norwegian_University_of_Science_and_Technology) (NTNU), renowned for its extensive technical facilities and diverse programs, alongside BI-Trondheim, a satellite campus of the Norwegian Business School. [78] Both institutions attract a considerable number of international students annually, offering various scholarships. [79]

[St. Olav's University Hospital](/St._Olavs_University_Hospital), the regional medical center for Central Norway, is located in the city center. It functions as a teaching hospital, fostering close collaboration with NTNU in both research and medical education.

[SINTEF](/SINTEF), a leading independent research organization in [Scandinavia](/Scandinavia), employs 1,800 individuals, with 1,300 based in Trondheim. [80] The Air Force Academy of the [Royal Norwegian Air Force](/Royal_Norwegian_Air_Force) is situated at Kuhaugen.

The [Geological Survey of Norway](/Geological_Survey_of_Norway), a prominent geoscientific institution with 220 employees (70% scientists), is headquartered in Lade.

Trondheim hosts eleven high schools. [Trondheim katedralskole](/Trondheim_katedralskole), founded in 1152, holds the distinction of being Norway's oldest upper secondary school ([gymnasium](/Gymnasium_(school))). Charlottenlund videregående skole stands as the largest in Sør-Trøndelag, with 1,100 students and 275 staff. Brundalen Skole is expanding to accommodate more students and hosts significant annual festivals.

Ila skole, established in 1770, is Trondheim's oldest primary school. [81]

### Media

[Adresseavisen](/Adresseavisen), founded in 1767, is the region's largest newspaper and Norway's oldest continuously published one. The Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation (NRK) maintains headquarters in both Tyholt, Trondheim, and Oslo. [82] On December 31, 2019, the digital-only local newspaper Nidaros was launched, aiming to compete with Adresseavisen. [83] Student media is represented by *Under Dusken* (student paper), [Radio Revolt](/Radio_Revolt) (student radio), and Student-TV (online video broadcasts).

Local radio stations include opt-out feeds of [NRK P1](/NRK_P1) and [NRK P1+](/NRK_P1%2B), a local version of NRK's [Yr](/Yr.no) radio station, and Radio Revolt. These, along with national stations, are accessible via [DAB+](/Digital_audio_broadcasting) across most of Trøndelag and through [internet radio](/Internet_radio). While commercial stations like Nea Radio and Radio Trøndelag are available, local commercial broadcasts within Trondheim Municipality proper are limited.

### Culture

#### Visual arts

The [Trondheim Art Museum](/Trondheim_Art_Museum) houses Norway's third-largest public art collection, primarily featuring Norwegian art from the past 150 years. [85]

The National Museum of Decorative Arts and Design (no) presents extensive collections of decorative arts and design, including notable tapestries by [Hannah Ryggen](/Hannah_Ryggen) and Norway's sole permanent exhibition of Japanese [arts and crafts](/Handicraft). [86]

Established in 1976, the Trøndelag Centre for Contemporary Art ([Trøndelag senter for samtidskunst](/Tr%C3%B8ndelag_senter_for_samtidskunst)) is a key venue for contemporary art. [87]

Two artist-run spaces, Galleri Blunk (founded in 2002 by students of the [Trondheim Academy of Fine Art](/Trondheim_Academy_of_Fine_Art)) and Babel (established in 2006 by Lademoen Artist Workshops), also contribute to the vibrant art scene. [88]

[Kunsthall Trondheim](/Kunsthall_Trondheim), inaugurated in its permanent location on Kongens gate in October 2016, showcases contemporary artistic practices. [89] [90]

The PoMo Museum (no), dedicated to [modern](/Modern_art) and [contemporary art](/Contemporary_art), opened its doors on Dronningens gate in February 2025. [91] [92]

#### Stage

[Trøndelag Teater](/Tr%C3%B8ndelag_Teater), the main regional theater, is housed in a building dating back to 1816, making it the oldest continuously operating theater in Scandinavia. [93] The city also supports the alternative theater house Teaterhuset Avant Garden and the theater company Teater Fusentast. [94]

#### Music

The [Ringve Museum](/Ringve_Museum) is dedicated to the history of music.

Trondheim boasts a dynamic music scene, with strong communities in rock, [jazz](/Jazz), and [classical music](/European_classical_music). The [music conservatory](/Music_conservatory) at [NTNU](/Norwegian_University_of_Science_and_Technology), recognized as one of the world's most innovative, and the municipal music school, Trondheim Kommunale Musikk- og Kulturskole, are central to the city's musical life. [95] [96] The [Trondheim Symphony Orchestra](/Trondheim_Symphony_Orchestra) and the [Trondheim Soloists](/Trondheim_Soloists) are internationally acclaimed ensembles. Trondheim hosts an annual Jazz festival and is home to the [Trondheim Jazz Orchestra](/Trondheim_Jazz_Orchestra). [97] The [Fjordgata Records](/Fjordgata_Records) label is also based here.

Notable classical musicians from Trondheim include violinist [Arve Tellefsen](/Arve_Tellefsen), [Elise Båtnes](/Elise_B%C3%A5tnes), and [Marianne Thorsen](/Marianne_Thorsen), as well as the [Nidaros Cathedral Boys' Choir](/Nidaros_Cathedral_Boys%27_Choir).

[Thomas Bergersen](/Thomas_Bergersen), a self-taught composer and multi-instrumentalist, co-founder of the production music company Two Steps From Hell, was born in Trondheim.

Prominent pop/rock artists and bands associated with Trondheim include [Åge Aleksandersen](/%C3%85ge_Aleksandersen), [Margaret Berger](/Margaret_Berger), [DumDum Boys](/DumDum_Boys), [Lasse Marhaug](/Lasse_Marhaug), [Gåte](/G%C3%A5te), [Keep Of Kalessin](/Keep_Of_Kalessin), [Lumsk](/Lumsk), [Motorpsycho](/Motorpsycho_(band)), [Kari Rueslåtten](/Kari_Ruesl%C3%A5tten), [the 3rd and the Mortal](/The_3rd_and_the_Mortal), [TNT](/TNT_(Norwegian_band)), [Tre Små Kinesere](/Tre_Sm%C3%A5_Kinesere), [the Kids](/The_Kids_(Norwegian_band)), [Bokassa](/Bokassa_(band)), Casino Steel (of [The Boys](/The_Boys_(UK_band))), Atrox, Bloodthorn, Manes, child prodigy [Malin Reitan](/Malin_Reitan), and [Aleksander With](/Aleksander_With). The punk scene is largely centered around [UFFA](/UFFA).

[Georg Kajanus](/Georg_Kajanus), creator of the bands [Eclection](/Eclection), [Sailor](/Sailor_(band)), and [DATA](/DATA_(band)), hails from Trondheim. The music production team [Stargate](/Stargate_(production_team)) also began its journey in the city.

Trondheim is also home to Rockheim, the national museum celebrating Norwegian popular music from the 1950s to the present day. [98] [99] [100]

#### Film

The city hosts a vibrant film scene, featuring three film festivals: Minimalen Short Film Fest and [Kosmorama International Film Fest](/Kosmorama) in March, and Trondheim Documentarfestival in November. Central Trondheim has two cinemas: Prinsen Kino and Nova Kinosenter.

#### Student culture

*The building of the [Studentersamfundet i Trondhjem](/Studentersamfundet_i_Trondhjem)*

With students constituting nearly a fifth of the population, Trondheim's culture is significantly shaped by its student body. [Studentersamfundet i Trondhjem](/Studentersamfundet_i_Trondhjem), the student society, is a prominent feature, housed in its distinctive circular, red building from 1929. As Norway's largest university, NTNU enrolls approximately 36,000 students. [101]

Student culture in Trondheim is characterized by a strong tradition of volunteerism. The student society itself is run by over 1,200 volunteers. [102] NTNUI, Norway's largest sports club, is another major volunteer organization. Students also organize two significant Norwegian culture festivals: [UKA](/UKA_(festival)) and [The International Student Festival in Trondheim](/Isfit) (ISFiT). NTNU lists over 200 student organizations with registered web pages. [103]

### In popular culture

Trondheim's cultural quirks are humorously parodied in the [Monty Python](/Monty_Python) album [Another Monty Python Record](/Another_Monty_Python_Record) through the fictional "Trondheim Hammer Dance." [104]

The city plays a crucial role in the [Command & Conquer: Tiberian Sun](/Command_%26_Conquer:_Tiberian_Sun) universe, serving as a key battleground for both factions.

In Orson Scott Card's *Ender's Game* series, Trondheim is depicted as the name of a planet within the Hundred Worlds.

Trondheim likely inspired the fictional city of Tronjheim in [The Inheritance Cycle](/The_Inheritance_Cycle).

### Sports and recreation

[Granåsen Ski Centre](/Gran%C3%A5sen_Ski_Centre) in Byåsen is a regular host of World Cup competitions in [ski jumping](/Ski_jumping), [biathlon](/Biathlon), and [cross-country skiing](/Cross-country_skiing_(sport)). It has hosted the [1997](/1997_FIS_Nordic_World_Ski_Championships) and will host the [2025 FIS Nordic World Ski Championships](/FIS_Nordic_World_Ski_Championships_2025). Trondheim's bid for the [2018 Winter Olympics](/2018_Winter_Olympics) was unsuccessful. Hiking and recreational skiing are popular, particularly in [Bymarka](/Bymarka), accessible via the tramway. Trondheim Golfklubb, one of Norway's oldest, features a nine-hole course in Byåsen. Byneset Golfklubb offers an 18-hole course that has hosted the [Norwegian Challenge](/Norwegian_Challenge), alongside a shorter nine-hole course. Klæbu Golfklubb provides another nine-hole course. A public par-3 course with city views is available in Byåsen.

[Rosenborg BK](/Rosenborg_BK)'s Lerkendal Stadium.

[Rosenborg BK](/Rosenborg_BK) is the city's premier top-flight football club, playing at [Lerkendal Stadion](/Lerkendal_stadion). They have secured 26 [Norwegian Premier League](/Norwegian_Premier_League) titles between 1967 and 2018 and have participated in the [UEFA Champions League](/UEFA_Champions_League) group stage 12 times, reaching the quarterfinals once. [Ranheim Fotball](/Ranheim_Fotball) achieved promotion to the top division in 2018, maintaining their place since the 2020 season. Their home ground is the [EXTRA Arena](/EXTRA_Arena).

[Byåsen IL](/By%C3%A5sen_IL) competes in the women's handball league and has participated in the [EHF Women's Champions League](/EHF_Women%27s_Champions_League). [Kolstad Håndball](/Kolstad_H%C3%A5ndball) plays in the men's league and has featured in the [2023–24](/2023%E2%80%9324_EHF_Champions_League) and [2024–25](/2024%E2%80%9325_EHF_Champions_League) seasons of the [EHF Champions League](/EHF_Champions_League). Both teams utilize [Trondheim Spektrum](/Trondheim_Spektrum) and Kolstad Arena for home games.

Trondheim is also considered the birthplace of the [basse](/Basse_(game)) game, played with a ball made of tightly bound rubber bands.

